1 Revisiting Lab 2: Exploring Rodents with ggplot2

Letâs start with the side-by-side boxplots you created in Lab 2, to visualize the distribution of weight within each species (not species ID!).

surveys |> 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = fct_reorder(species, weight, .fun = median, .desc = TRUE), y = weight)) + 
  geom_jitter(color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.05) + 
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)

surveys %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = fct_reorder(species, weight, .fun = median, .desc = TRUE), y = weight)) +
  geom_jitter(color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.05) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  coord_flip() +  # Flip the axes
  labs(x = "Median Weight", y = "") +  
  theme(
    axis.title.x = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"), 
    axis.title.y = element_blank())

2 Time-Series Plot

Warning

This is a new section, meaning a new plot. In other words, this is not a continuation of the box-plot from above.

This week, we focused on learning skills related to working with dates, but we have yet to make a very common type of plot â the time-series plot. Weâll use this plot to motivate a second type of factor reordering!

yearly_weights <- surveys %>%
  group_by(year, genus) %>%
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')


ggplot(yearly_weights, aes(x = year, y = mean_weight, color = genus, group = genus)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    title = "Avg Weights Over Time",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Average Weight (g)",
    color = "Genus") +
  theme_minimal()

surveys <- surveys %>%
  mutate(year = year(ymd(date)))

yearly_weights <- surveys %>%
  group_by(year, genus) %>%
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')

surveys <- surveys %>%

# Create the plot
ggplot(yearly_weights, aes(x = year, y = mean_weight, color = genus, group = genus)) +

    x = "Year",
    y = "Average Weight (g)",
    color = "Genus" ) +
  theme_minimal() +

3 Caputures over the Week

###
surveys$day_of_week <- factor(surveys$day_of_week, 
                              levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))
surveys %>%
  filter(!is.na(day_of_week)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday")) +
  labs(title = "Rodents Captured Each Day of the Week",
    x = "Day of the Week",
    y = "Captures") +
  theme_minimal()

## Revisiting Lab 2: Exploring Rodents with ggplot2

Let's start with the side-by-side boxplots you created in Lab 2, to visualize the distribution of weight within each species (not species ID!).

```{r}
#| eval: true

surveys |> 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = fct_reorder(species, weight, .fun = median, .desc = TRUE), y = weight)) + 
  geom_jitter(color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.05) + 
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)

surveys %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = fct_reorder(species, weight, .fun = median, .desc = TRUE), y = weight)) +
  geom_jitter(color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.05) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  coord_flip() +  # Flip the axes
  labs(x = "Median Weight", y = "") +  
  theme(
    axis.title.x = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"), 
    axis.title.y = element_blank())
```
